snippet.textDisplay: I use a 43.5 inch 2008 MacGregor MT460 with an extra stiff steel shaft. I hit it just as far as anything since 2008 and I've tested everything (sort of a club ho). I'm  done. I'm just not buying it. Think about it. All around 460cc and same coefficient of restitution and all close to the same shape. Maybe you can squeeze out an extra 5 yards but my steel shaft puts me in the fairway at least 25% more of the time. When has Rick ever gained more than 1 club distance? Seems to me he's always around 300 yards. Heres a real tip: Spend your money on Pro Vs if you want to gain distance.

snippet.textDisplay:
Hey Rick!

Western PA golfer here, 9 handicap. First off, your content is outstanding. Really appreciate all you do.

I have had new drivers and I decided to change things up. I bought an almost new Titleist 905R, you know, the driver with the red arrows that everyone remembers. I tested it vs my newer clubs and put the same shaft in it ( Proforce V2 X) and I was really connecting. Longer and I liked how it felt heavier almost.

I'm curious if this was a club fitting anomaly (I cut my driver down 2" for comfort, control, and off the deck options) or if this club is on par with modern tech.

What are your thoughts? I doubt you'll see this comment but I would really appreciate your knowledge.

Best,
Oakes

snippet.textDisplay: What is the point of doing an "on course" test with both drivers if you don't actually measure where each ball is going or even mark them separately and retrieve them? Also, no mention of total distance. You can do better, Rick. Cheers.
